<div class="page">
  <header class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">React on Rails Pro &middot; RSC Flagship Demo</p>
    <h1>Flagship Task Board</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      A real CRUD app, streamed by Rails through React on Rails Pro. The board
      below starts as a React Server Component, sends HTML from the Node renderer,
      then React 19 hydrates the client component and Redux Toolkit store.
      ActiveRecord owns the data; React owns the UI.
    </p>
    <div class="hero-links">
      <a href="https://github.com/shakacode/react-on-rails-demo-flagship" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Source on GitHub</a>
      <a href="https://reactonrails.com" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">React on Rails docs</a>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main class="surface">
    <%= stream_react_component("TasksApp", props: @tasks_props) %>
  </main>

  <footer class="explain">
    <div class="explain-card">
      <h2>Prove streaming to yourself</h2>
      <p>
        Run <code>curl -s localhost:3000 | grep task-card</code> &mdash; the task markup
        is in the streamed HTML response, not injected by client JavaScript.
        <code>bin/smoke</code> automates exactly that check.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="explain-card">
      <h2>Where to look</h2>
      <p>
        <code>app/controllers/tasks_controller.rb</code> streams the view,
        <code>app/views/tasks/index.html.erb</code> mounts the component, and
        <code>app/javascript/src/TasksApp/</code> holds the React + Redux Toolkit code.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="explain-card">
      <h2>Error states included</h2>
      <p>
        Submit an empty title to see Rails validations surface in the banner, or stop
        the server and try a change to see the network error path.
      </p>
    </div>
  </footer>
</div>
